metadata.name: Chance #119
metadata.description:
The world is chaotic at first glance. Throwing a die, trading stocks or cryptocurrencies, or simply walking through a crowded city center can have unpredictable outcomes.

Computers are different. Algorithms are deterministic by design. Given the same input, they always produce the same result. In reverse, it‚Äôs impossible for a computer to produce a string that is truly unpredictable. What is usually an advantage becomes a problem in cryptography.

To provide truly random numbers for encryption, Silicon Graphics filed a patent in 1996 for Lavarand. By taking photos of a bunch of physical lava lamps, they generated the random numbers needed for privacy and security in the computer age. While the original patent expired, the most important internet infrastructure provider, Cloudflare*, built their own lava lamp wall in their San Francisco headquarters. They are used to provide SSL/TLS encryption to their customers.

Chance turns the Lavarand concept on its head. It generates a simulated lava lamp from the unique seed that is stored in each generative NFT. The ThreeJS simulation runs in the browser. Unlike the physical lava lamps, their movements are determined because they follow mathematical calculations that always produce the same movements and shapes. Under which conditions could the simulation become as complex as the physical lamps?

Thank you to the three.js community and the creators of the Marching Cubes example (greggman, Henrik Rydg√•rd). Optimized for Chrome version 105.


*according to Forbes ‚ÄúHow Cloudflare Became The Most Important Internet Company Nobody Has Heard Of‚Äù (Dec 4, 2020)

metadata.name: Tangentum #235
metadata.description:
We live in a multiverse: an infinite-dimensional space of variants. Everything exists here. Everything is possible. Each subset of a multiverse has its own unique laws of physics, a set of rules, and its own distinct features.

Tangentum creates a projection of a random multiverse subset to a 2-dimensional plane. Each variation is a unique representation of the force field, that exists somewhere at some point in time.

This work starts a series of my visual exploration of functions, continuity, and boundedness, and I would love to share it with you.


Please use fullscreen or download artwork in high resolution for a better viewing experience.

Tested with Chrome 107, Safari, and Firefox. Chrome is recommended, other browsers are slower on this artwork.

Saving with high and ultra-high resolution may take a while, please be patient.


Made with love and p5js


Controls in fullscreen:
[1] - save PNG 2700 x 1800
[2] - save PNG 5400 x 3800
[3] - save PNG 10800 x 7600
[4] - save PNG 16200 x 11400

metadata.name: (kinder)Garden, Monuments #105
metadata.description:
When Yazid and Zancan started their fxcollab journey, they knew very little about each other. They learnt about their rich cultural differences, their complementary graphic styles, and a 7-hour timezone difference. What they did have in common was each had two kids about the same age (one a pair of girls, the other boys).

Every kid was born a builder; every kid likes to sit in nature. It‚Äôs their way of discovering the world and dreaming of their future accomplishments. While they marvel at the heights of the cities and monuments they construct out of stacks of cubes, parents marvel at their ability to elaborate an unlimited range of worlds out of a limited range of materials. 

This project celebrates the humble and versatile cube. A deceptively simple yet powerful object of play and learning, regardless of age, whether you‚Äôre stacking them up in a sandbox, or learning 3D graphics for the first time. 

This project is dedicated to kids, those who were once children, to the dreamers and builders who still enjoy playing with cubes.

Coded in Vanilla JS, the project combines Yazid's iconic ‚ÄúHashed/Hatched‚Äù aesthetic incorporated into childhood wooden toy block structures, and Zancan's signature lush foliage and framework, which enables all iterations to be plottable.
 
Controls (in live view):
- Press [s] to get a SVG file suited for plotters
- Click on the image to download a 4K resolution PNG

metadata.name: Ceremony #41
metadata.description:
This series celebrates fxhash turning one. #fxhashturnsone

I‚Äôm so grateful for this place and have ho idea how to adequately articulate how much this platform has changed my life, but it has. A million thanks to the team. You are so appreciated as are the artists and collectors that have made this such a beautiful community. ü•Ç

Definitely check out ‚ÄúForever‚Äù mode by tapping ‚ÄúF‚Äù or mouse click/tap ‚Äî it will animate (you guessed it) forever and will change its layout every 365 frames, in honor of this wonderful year, and every year after. Some forever modes will ‚Äúnever forget‚Äù and others will fade as they progress. No idea if that‚Äôs a metaphor but it is a trait, that much I know.

All primary sales are donated to Code/Art, which is a charity that uses ‚Äú‚Ä¶Art to Inspire Girls in Computer Science.‚Äù Read about Code/Art here: https://www.code-art.com/

Ceremony uses public domain art (which is the original, more implicit version CC0) made exclusively by women.

See fxtext article linked from the project page for a gallery of the source material and other notes.

Ceremony is also CC0, so feel free use anything here in other projects.

You can read more about CC0 here:
https://creativecommons.org/share-your-work/public-domain/cc0/

F : ‚ÄúForever‚Äù mode (tap after initial render completes)
P : Pause/Play
(mouse click/tap also works to start ‚ÄúForever‚Äù mode or Pause/Play)

A : Add Grain (only works when paused in ‚ÄúForever‚Äù mode.)
G : Toggle Grain (resets the whole piece)
M : Toggle Matte (resets the whole piece)

S : Save Image
1 -> 6 : Set pixel density (resets the whole piece)
(Default pixel density is 1 @ 2000x2000)

If you want to start in "Forever" mode, you can append "&forever=true" to the url in the live view.
You can also add pixel density to the url by appending ‚Äú&density=2‚Äù (or 3, 4, etc) to have it render at higher resolutions by default.

metadata.name: Antigravity #294
metadata.description:
To change size or quality, open the IPFS link in a separate window and append to its url a string like `&quality=400&tiles=9,16`. You may notice two parameters in it: `quality` and `tiles`.

`quality` is an integer from 1 to ~1000, the better the quality ‚Äî the slower the rendering. Default is 200.

`tiles` is a number of 256√ó256 px tiles to render. Can be an integer (for square images) or two integers separated with a¬†comma (for rectangular). `tiles=9,16` will make an image with width of 9√ó256 px = 2304 px and height of 16√ó256 px = 4096 px. If not set, adapts to screen size.

Press `s` to save the image.
